  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering frameworks\n- Limited regulatory oversight\n\n2. 1980s-1990s\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986, US)\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More comprehensive reporting requirements\n\n3. Post-9/11 Era\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Stricter international sanctions\n- Expanded terrorist financing prevention\n\n4. Recent Developments\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Advanced data analytics and AI integration\n\n5. Key Legislative Trends\n- Global standardization of anti-money laundering protocols\n- Broader regulatory scope\n- More sophisticated detection mechanisms\n- Increased corporate accountability\n- Cross-border information sharing\n\n6. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Cryptocurrency transactions\n- Complex financial technologies\n- Politically Exposed Persons (PEP) tracking\n- Enhanced risk-based approaches\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to evolving financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
